subsection.p:
If \alpha \lt 0, then 
            J
            =
            \begin{pmatrix}
            2 \sqrt{\alpha} & 0 \\
            0 & -1
            \end{pmatrix}
            \text{ or }
            \begin{pmatrix}
            -2 \sqrt{\alpha} & 0 \\
            0 & -1
            \end{pmatrix}.
        In the first case, we have a saddle since the eigenvalues are real and of opposite sign. In the second case, we have a nodal sink, since both eigenvalues are negative.  The two equilibrium solutions move in opposite directions as \alpha decreases. We can summarize what happens for various values of \alpha with a bifurcation diagram such as the one in .
